          "title": "Recognition as divine gift",
          "body": "The verb *dianoigo* (\"to open thoroughly\") appears three times in the chapter — eyes opened (v. 31), Scriptures opened (v. 32), minds opened (v. 45). In every case Christ is the agent. Luke's pastoral and theological point is striking: resurrection cognition is not a natural conclusion drawn from evidence; it is a divine opening. The Emmaus pair walk beside the risen Jesus for hours without recognizing Him; the Eleven see Him standing among them and think He is a ghost. Only when Christ acts on the perceiver — opening eyes, opening Scripture, opening mind — does recognition occur. This anticipates Paul's later argument in 2 Corinthians 4:3-6 and Ephesians 1:17-18 that spiritual sight is gift, not achievement."
