          "body": "Verses 27 and 44 are the strongest statements in the New Testament about christological reading of the Old. Jesus interprets \"in all the Scriptures the things concerning Himself,\" beginning with *Moses and all the prophets*, and later names the canonical tripartite structure: *the Law of Moses, the Prophets, and the Psalms*. This is the formal Hebrew canon (Torah, Nevi'im, Ketuvim — with Psalms standing for the Writings as the largest book). Luke is anchoring apostolic hermeneutics: the Old Testament is not a problem the New Testament solves; it is the witness the risen Christ Himself authorizes. The church's earliest preaching (Acts 2, 3, 7, 13) executes this hermeneutic."
